    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Supreme Court's interpretation of the 2nd Amendment, particularly in the landmark case District of Columbia v. Heller, is a prime example of judicial activism. The founders intended the right to bear arms as a collective right tied to militia service, not an individual right. The Court's decision to recognize an individual right to bear arms without any connection to militia service is a significant departure from the original intent of the Constitution. The better legal argument is that the founders' original intent should guide our interpretation of the 2nd Amendment, not modern judicial activism.",
